Decision Tree Pruning¶

Definition:¶

In machine learning and data mining, pruning is a technique associated with decision trees. Pruning reduces the size of decision trees by removing parts of the tree that do not provide power to classify instances. Decision trees are the most susceptible out of all the machine learning algorithms to overfitting, and effective pruning can reduce this likelihood. We will go over two techniques to help with overfitting :-

  1. pre-pruning or early stopping
  2. post-pruning

Let's first understand how overfitting and underfitting happens in Decision Trees. When the decision tree model memorizes its training data so well that it is learning noise on top of the signal, then it is actually overfitting. Generally in this case the decision tree is very long and a leaves can contain very less number of instances( as less as one single instance). And when the tree is too short and simple to learn pattern in data. So the aim of the decison tree pruning is to balance between the simplicity and the accuracy.

Post Pruning by removing nodes which does not contribute to improve accuracy:¶

def num_nodes(clf_local, n):
    if(n!=-1):
        nodes=1
    else:
        return 0
    left_nodes=num_nodes(clf_local, clf_local.tree_.children_left[n])
    right_nodes=num_nodes(clf_local, clf_local.tree_.children_right[n])
    nodes=nodes+left_nodes+right_nodes
    return nodes

In [22]:
node_depth = np.zeros(shape=n_nodes, dtype=np.int64)
is_leaves = np.zeros(shape=n_nodes, dtype=bool)
stack = [(0, -1)]  # seed is the root node id and its parent depth
while len(stack) > 0:
    node_id, parent_depth = stack.pop()
    node_depth[node_id] = parent_depth + 1
    
    # If we have a test node
    if (children_left[node_id] != children_right[node_id]):
        stack.append((children_left[node_id], parent_depth + 1))
        stack.append((children_right[node_id], parent_depth + 1))
    else:
        is_leaves[node_id] = True
max_Depth = max(node_depth)
print("Max Depth is",max_Depth)

for i in range(max_Depth,5,-1):
    clf1 = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='entropy',max_depth = i,min_samples_leaf=1)
    clf1 = clf1.fit(x_train,y_train)
    score1=clf1.score(x_vald,y_vald)
    if(score1 > best_score1):
        print("\nNew tree: --------------------------------------")
        print("Improved Validation Score from {0} to {1} for height {2}".format(best_score1, score1, i))
        score2=clf1.score(x_test,y_test)
        print("Test Score = {0} ".format(score2))
        n_nodes1 = clf1.tree_.node_count
        print("Number of nodes: ",n_nodes1)
        best_score1 = score1
        clf_local = clf1
        dot_data_local = tree.export_graphviz(clf_local, out_file=None) 
        graph_local = graphviz.Source(dot_data_local) 
        graph_local.render("diabetes_Tree_pre_height"+str(i)+".dot")
        #print(list(x_train))
        dot_data_local = tree.export_graphviz(clf_local, out_file=None, 
                              feature_names=list(x_train),  
                              class_names=list(y_train),  
                              filled=True, rounded=True,  
                              special_characters=True)  
        graph1_local = graphviz.Source(dot_data_local) 


        (graph_local,) = pydot.graph_from_dot_file("diabetes_Tree_pre_height"+str(i)+".dot")
        graph_local.write_png("diabetes_Tree_pre_height"+str(i)+".png")
        filename="diabetes_Tree_pre_height"+str(i)+".png"
        img = Image.open(filename)
        img=img.resize((1600,1000))
        img.save(filename)
        images.append(imageio.imread(filename))
        graph1_local

imageio.mimsave("DT_Pruning_low_pre_height.gif", images, duration=0.5)
